<section id="overview" class="card">
  <h2>City Overview</h2>
  <p>On the southern coast of Brazil, surrounded by lush green mountains, sandy beaches, and turquoise waters, lies the city of Alimora. Founded in 2125, Alimora supports two million citizens through a zero-waste circular economy and an exceptional quality of life.</p>
  <p>Residents live in Florimoras — communities made of six Bloom towers surrounding a central STEM tower. These structures integrate housing, farming, manufacturing, healthcare, and recreation to ensure accessibility, sustainability, and inclusivity for all.</p>
</section>

<section id="problem" class="card">
  <h2>Defined Problem</h2>
  <p>Before Alimora, southern Brazil faced severe food waste and inefficient waste management. Over 4,800 tons of food were wasted daily, polluting waterways and increasing food insecurity.</p>
</section>

<section id="solution" class="card">
  <h2>Overview of the Solution</h2>
  <p>Alimora eliminates food waste by integrating farming directly into residential towers. Hydroponic-Aeroponic Integrated Life Systems (HAILS) grow food efficiently, while anaerobic digestion converts waste into energy and fertilizer, creating a fully circular system.</p>

  <h3>Solution 1: Florimoras & Vertical Farming</h3>
  <p>Each Florimora contains six Blooms and one STEM tower. CRISPR-engineered crops, automated robotics, and Nutriwatch-guided food distribution ensure efficient, personalized nutrition with zero waste.</p>

  <h3>Solution 2: Waste-to-Energy Systems</h3>
  <p>AI-guided waste separation feeds Digestion, After-treatment, and Pyrolysis (DAP) facilities. Methane is converted into hydrogen and carbon, powering Solid Oxide Fuel Cells (SOFCs) paired with thermophotovoltaics for up to 80% efficiency.</p>
</section>

<section id="engineering" class="card">
  <h2>Engineering Roles & Risks</h2>
  <p>Bioengineers, mechanical engineers, chemical engineers, and agricultural engineers collaborate to manage risks such as methane leaks, energy demand, and crop diversity limitations. Continuous monitoring, closed-loop systems, and optimized energy cycles ensure long-term reliability.</p>
</section>

